%BOM---------------------
Date:6/2/1997 3:55:00 PM
From:sea_biscuit

Over the weekend, I was reading Bill Staton's "The America's Finest Companies
Investment Plan". He recommends non-dividend paying stocks with consistent
earnings increases (at least 10 years) for a regular (i.e. taxable) account and
stocks with consistent dividend increases of at least 10 years (in other words,
Dividend Achievers) for a non-taxable account like IRA.

In the taxable account, any company whose annual earnings suffer a decline
should be sold off, and in the tax-sheltered account, any company which fails
to increase its annual dividend is thrown out.

Some of his other suggestions are : to restrict the total number of companies
in the two accounts to about 10 or 12 at the most, with each company
representing a different sector (to keep the portfolios truly diversified), to
dollar-cost average on an annual basis and to keep the portfolios reasonably
balanced, keeping in mind the costs for commissions and also, in the case of
the regular account, taxes.

Regards

Dipy.
