Date:6/4/1997 1:18:00 PM
From:sea_biscuit

Paul Senior :

This approach is meant for people who don't want to be bothered by the
day-to-day events in the stock-market and the economy, and who cannot go into
the detailed analyses of why a company hit an earnings glitch. In short, this
is really a substitute for mutual fund investing.

The important thing to remember is -- once you implement this strategy, you
have to follow it to the letter. A little tweak here and there, and pretty
soon, you realize you have drifted from the strategy!

I understand that it would be highly profitable to buy a stock when the company
hits an earnings glitch. But it takes a lot of research and analysis to
separate a bombed-out stock from a Super Stock (to use Kenneth Fisher's
terminology from his book, "Super Stocks"). You could do this too, if you have
the time and the ability to do so. Just keep the two portfolios separate and
distinct.

Regards

Dipy.
