Date:6/6/1997 12:50:00 PM
From:sea_biscuit

Hi Paul Senior :

I checked out the company that you mentioned -- Sigma Aldrich. According to the
1995 edition of Staton's book, the company has been an Earnings Achiever AND a
Dividend Achiever for more than 20 years.

If the company hit an earnings glitch but still increased its dividend, it
would continue to remain in the list of AFCs (America's Finest Companies). The
fact that there was a dividend increase in spite of an earnings increase can be
interpreted as a signal and reassurance from the company that it is just a
one-year setback. However, if in the following year, it cut its dividend, then
(and only then) you should sell the stock.

Of course, this means that your taxable portfolio has to have companies that
pay dividends! So are we back to Square One? Probably not. If you have a
cut-off like say, the yield of the taxable portfolio should not be more than
half the market yield, you can still keep your taxable dividends down. In this
case, you are making a trade-off between portfolio turnover and paying taxes on
dividends.

Regards

Dipy.
