"Quality" is a more correct description here than "value".

Anyway, Staton says (and I think he's right about this) that this approach (of
owning a portfolio of 8 to 10 of America's Finest Companies, buying regularly
and adding to the portfolio, and selling only occasionally) makes you emulate
Buffett's style of investing.

Buffett is certainly not a "value" investor. He is one of those rarities -- a
long-term growth investor, and the only other person who comes anywhere close
to him is Peter Lynch.

