%BOM---------------------
Date:6/8/1997 8:16:00 PM
From:sea_biscuit

Somebody asked as to how this can be called "value investing". Well, as I was
reading through the book again, I realized exactly how! Staton says that we
should keep the portfolio reasonably balanced. However, he does *not* recommend
selling any stock for that purpose. Instead, he suggests adjusting *new buying*
to achieve balance.

As an example, let's say we invested $1000 each in five companies C1, C2, C3,
C4 and C5 at the beginning of the year. At the end of the year we find that C1
and C2 appreciated by 15% each, C3 by 20%. C4 by 10% but C5 *lost* 20%.

Let's say all the companies qualified to be on the portfolio for the following
year too. The total value of the portfolio at the end of the first year is
$5400. If we are now adding say, another $5000 to the portfolio, then the total
would be $10,400 and each company should be about $2100. So we should put $1300
in C5 and distribute the remaining amount over the other four companies. That
is, 26% of the new money is put in C5, instead of the usual 20%. This means we
*are* using some kind of value criteria when we follow this strategy.

Dipy.
