Date:6/17/1997 8:05:00 AM
From:Lonnie Yearwood

Paul, not much in the way of numbers, but, at least, recent (6/17):

Fila Stock Tumbles
After Company
Projects Results

----

By Janet Morrissey
AP-Dow Jones News Service

NEW YORK -- Fila Holding SpA stock fell 12% on news the company will fall short
of analysts'expectations when it releases its second-quarter results next
month.

On Friday, the Biella, Italy, maker of athletic shoes and apparel said it
expects its second-quarter revenue and earnings to miss analysts' estimates
because of "a weak U.S. footwear and apparel market," order cancellations and
problems associated with the company's warehouse software system. It said
investments designed to strengthen its product range also will cut into the
bottom line.

Fila projects second-quarter earnings of 53 cents to 60 cents a share. Six
analysts surveyed by First Call Inc. had projected the company would earn 83
cents a share. Four of the six have now revised that figure to 56 cents.

First Call said analysts also revised their estimates for Fila's 1997 and 1998
results. Four of six analysts lowered their per-share projections to $3.53 from
$4 for 1997, and to $3.80 from $4.52 for 1998.

In the 1996 second quarter, Fila Holding earned $25.9 million, or 98 cents a
share, on revenue of $322 million.

Fila Holding's American depository shares yesterday fell $4.50 to $32.875 in
New York Stock Exchange composite trading on volume of nearly 1.4 million
shares. Average daily volume is 242,506.

One analyst, Michael Conn from Gruntal & Co., concurred. "Clearly the demand
continues to be quite sluggish in the U.S., and its reverberations on earnings
is starting to show," he said. "The look of the products and the type of
marketing have not evolved" to the point where consumers are jumping on the
Fila bandwagon, Mr. Conn said.

Fila is also under pressure from designers that have elbowed their way into the
athletic footwear and apparel market, such as Tommy Hilfiger Corp., Donna Karan
International Inc. -- and, more recently,
Polo Ralph Lauren Corp.

"The product just isn't there and it isn't selling in the U.S.," said one
analyst who has been bearish on the maker of athletic clothes and footwear
since he began covering the stock last December.
